<!--
  Proxmox VE -> Wazuh custom rules — proxmox_rules.xml.
  For a Proxmox VE host (Debian-based) running the Wazuh agent.

  WHY THIS IS A *RULES-ONLY* PACK (no custom decoders needed)
  ====================================================================================
  A Proxmox host runs a FULL Wazuh agent, so every field these rules need is ALREADY
  produced by STOCK decoders — no custom decoder is required (and none would even win:
  stock decoders in ruleset/decoders load BEFORE etc/decoders, so a bespoke pveproxy/
  pvedaemon decoder could not pre-empt the stock one). Specifically:
    - pvedaemon lines -> stock 0440-proxmox-ve_decoders.xml, base rule 87200.
    - pveproxy access.log lines -> stock 0375-web-accesslog decoder sets srcip/url/id;
      stock base rule 31100 (category web-log), 31101 (HTTP 4xx). We specialise that chain.
    - /etc/pve FIM -> stock syscheck parents 550/553/554 set the 'file' field.

  WHAT STOCK ALREADY COVERS (do NOT duplicate — these ship in Wazuh 4.x, rules 0495):
    - 87201 (L6) PVE auth failure (@pam/@pve), 87202 (L10) PVE brute force (8/120s,
      same_source_ip, T1110), 87203 (L3) PVE auth success.  -> kept as the safety net; we
      do NOT add rule_exclude and do NOT re-implement pvedaemon auth here.
  WHAT STOCK LEAVES SILENT (all of this routes to 87200 L0) — the gap this pack fills:
    - VM/CT lifecycle (create/DESTROY/backup/migrate), pveum admin/token, /etc/pve FIM.

  LEVEL DISCIPLINE (triage gate = L10; >=10 reaches analyst triage):
    - destruction & rogue-admin (user.cfg / priv / corosync) -> L10 immediately (no freq gate).
    - single auth failure -> L8 (below gate); brute-force composite -> L10.
    - routine admin (VM create / vzdump / migrate / pveum) -> L6-L8 (visibility, below gate).
    - status/housekeeping -> handled by stock 87200/pvestatd, not re-rated here.

  Rule IDs 100390-100394, 100416-100423 (verify the range is free on your manager before installing).
  NB: 100416-100423 were renumbered from 100400-100409 to avoid colliding with
  socfortress 100100-MITRE_TECHNIQUES_FROM_SYSMON_EVENT1.xml (which owns 100400-100415):
    grep -rhoE 'rule id="(10039[0-4]|1004(1[6-9]|2[0-3]))"' \
      /var/ossec/etc/rules/ /var/ossec/ruleset/rules/   # expect: empty

  *** VALIDATE BEFORE TRUSTING (two known unknowns) ***
    a) The UPID task-type tokens (qmdestroy, vzdestroy, vzdump, qmmigrate, vzcreate, ...)
       and whether pveum operations log via pvedaemon at all are from the documented UPID
       format, NOT guaranteed on every PVE version. Confirm against a real line:
         journalctl -u pvedaemon -S '7 days ago' | grep 'task UPID' \
           | grep -oE 'UPID:[^ ]+' | sort -u
       then feed a sample through /var/ossec/bin/wazuh-logtest.
       If pveum has no pvedaemon UPID line, rule 100394 simply never fires (harmless) and
       /etc/pve/user.cfg FIM (100419) remains the reliable rogue-admin/token detector.
    b) pveproxy may log srcip as an IPv4-mapped ::ffff:1.2.3.4. same_source_ip works either
       way; MISP IP-IOC correlation (100210/100211) may need the ::ffff: prefix normalised.
-->
<group name="proxmox,proxmox-ve,">

  <!-- ============================================================
       A. PVE task lifecycle + admin plane  (chain off stock base 87200)
       87200 = "pvedaemon messages grouped" (decoded_as pvedaemon, L0). The stock
       pvedaemon decoder extracts no fields from task lines, so we match the raw
       message. UPID layout: UPID:<node>:<pid>:<pstart>:<starttime>:<DTYPE>:<id>:<user>:
       ============================================================ -->

  <!-- New VM/CT created or restored — routine admin, visibility only. -->
  <rule id="100390" level="6">
    <if_sid>87200</if_sid>
    <match type="pcre2">starting task UPID:[^:]+:[^:]+:[^:]+:[^:]+:(qmcreate|vzcreate|pct_create|qmrestore|vzrestore)</match>
    <description>Proxmox: VM/CT created or restored — verify the initiating user and VMID.</description>
    <mitre><id>T1578.002</id></mitre>
    <group>proxmox_vm_lifecycle,</group>
  </rule>

  <!-- VM/CT DESTROYED — immediate triage. An actor with PVE access can wipe guests on the
       hypervisor. No frequency gate: any destroy is review-worthy. -->
  <rule id="100391" level="10">
    <if_sid>87200</if_sid>
    <match type="pcre2">starting task UPID:[^:]+:[^:]+:[^:]+:[^:]+:(qmdestroy|vzdestroy|pct_destroy)</match>
    <description>Proxmox: VM/CT DESTROYED — verify authorised maintenance or investigate destructive activity.</description>
    <mitre><id>T1578.001</id></mitre>
    <mitre><id>T1485</id></mitre>
    <group>proxmox_vm_lifecycle,proxmox_destruction,</group>
  </rule>

  <!-- vzdump backup job started — visibility (exfil/anti-recovery context). -->
  <rule id="100392" level="6">
    <if_sid>87200</if_sid>
    <match type="pcre2">starting task UPID:[^:]+:[^:]+:[^:]+:[^:]+:vzdump</match>
    <description>Proxmox: vzdump backup job initiated — verify it is a scheduled job.</description>
    <mitre><id>T1005</id></mitre>
    <group>proxmox_backup,</group>
  </rule>

  <!-- VM/CT migration — unexpected migration can indicate guest hijack or HA manipulation. -->
  <rule id="100393" level="7">
    <if_sid>87200</if_sid>
    <match type="pcre2">starting task UPID:[^:]+:[^:]+:[^:]+:[^:]+:(qmmigrate|vzmigrate)</match>
    <description>Proxmox: VM/CT migration initiated — verify authorised maintenance.</description>
    <mitre><id>T1578</id></mitre>
    <group>proxmox_vm_lifecycle,</group>
  </rule>

  <!-- pveum user/role/ACL/token admin op (BEST-EFFORT — see validation note (a)).
       Primary, reliable detector for rogue admins/tokens is the user.cfg FIM rule 100419.
       L8: below the gate (legitimate admin ops happen); token creation escalates via 100419. -->
  <rule id="100394" level="8">
    <if_sid>87200</if_sid>
    <match type="pcre2">UPID:[^:]+:[^:]+:[^:]+:[^:]+:pveum|\bpveum (useradd|usermod|aclmod|tokenadd|tokenmod|roleadd|rolemod)</match>
    <description>Proxmox: PVE user/role/ACL/token management (pveum) — verify authorised admin action.</description>
    <mitre><id>T1136.001</id></mitre>
    <mitre><id>T1098</id></mitre>
    <group>proxmox_admin,account_management,</group>
  </rule>

  <!-- ============================================================
       B. PVE web-UI / API auth via pveproxy access.log
       PREREQ: collect /var/log/pveproxy/access.log as a localfile (see README).
       Stock 0375-web-accesslog decodes srcip + url + id(status); stock 31100 (base,
       category web-log) and 31101 (4xx) fire. We specialise to /access/ticket so analysts
       see "PVE login" not "web 400", and add a tighter brute-force composite. srcip is
       canonical -> MISP IP-IOC rules 100210/100211 auto-flag known-bad sources.
       (Additive to stock 87201/87202, which see the same auth from pvedaemon; the access.log
       uniquely provides the source IP on SUCCESS, which the pvedaemon success decoder lacks.)
       ============================================================ -->

  <!-- Successful PVE web-UI / API login (HTTP 200 on /access/ticket) — note the source IP.
       NB: PVE tickets auto-renew ~every 30 min per open browser tab, so a steady trickle of
       these is normal; correlate against prior failures before treating one as a new login.
       if_sid MUST include 31108: stock 31108 "Ignored URLs" (L0) claims every 2xx/3xx
       web-accesslog event as a child of 31100, and once it fires only ITS children are
       evaluated — with if_sid=31100 alone this rule is never reached (verified by logtest).
       Dual-parent idiom mirrors stock 31103/31509. 4xx lines skip 31108, so 100417
       (child of 31101) is unaffected. -->
  <rule id="100416" level="4">
    <if_sid>31100,31108</if_sid>
    <url>/access/ticket</url>
    <id>^200</id>
    <description>Proxmox: PVE web-UI/API login SUCCESS from $(srcip) [HTTP $(id) $(url)].</description>
    <mitre><id>T1078</id></mitre>
    <group>authentication_success,proxmox_auth,</group>
  </rule>

  <!-- Failed PVE web-UI / API login (4xx on /access/ticket). Single failure stays below gate. -->
  <rule id="100417" level="8">
    <if_sid>31101</if_sid>
    <url>/access/ticket</url>
    <description>Proxmox: PVE web-UI/API login FAILURE from $(srcip) [HTTP $(id) $(url)].</description>
    <mitre><id>T1110</id></mitre>
    <group>authentication_failed,proxmox_auth,</group>
  </rule>

  <!-- HTTP-layer brute force: 6 failures / 120s from one source -> triage. Tighter than the
       stock web composite 31151 (14/90s) because this is a hypervisor management plane. -->
  <rule id="100418" level="10" frequency="6" timeframe="120">
    <if_matched_sid>100417</if_matched_sid>
    <same_source_ip />
    <description>Proxmox: PVE web-UI/API brute force from $(srcip) — repeated login failures.</description>
    <mitre><id>T1110.001</id></mitre>
    <group>authentication_failures,proxmox_auth,brute_force,</group>
  </rule>

  <!-- ============================================================
       C. /etc/pve FIM escalation  (chain off stock syscheck 550/553/554)
       /etc/pve is a FUSE/pmxcfs mount -> scheduled scan only (no realtime); see the README
       agent.conf snippet for the scan + noise-ignore config and the FUSE caveat.
       ============================================================ -->

  <!-- PVE user/permission database: any change can mean a rogue admin or token was added. -->
  <rule id="100419" level="10">
    <if_sid>550,553,554</if_sid>
    <field name="file">^/etc/pve/user\.cfg$</field>
    <description>Proxmox FIM: /etc/pve/user.cfg changed — possible rogue PVE admin/ACL/token addition.</description>
    <mitre><id>T1098</id></mitre>
    <mitre><id>T1136.001</id></mitre>
    <group>syscheck,fim_escalation,account_management,</group>
  </rule>

  <!-- Cluster CA key / token secrets / TFA under /etc/pve/priv. -->
  <rule id="100420" level="10">
    <if_sid>550,553,554</if_sid>
    <field name="file" type="pcre2">^/etc/pve/priv/</field>
    <description>Proxmox FIM: /etc/pve/priv/ key or secret changed ($(file)) — verify authorised key rotation.</description>
    <mitre><id>T1552</id></mitre>
    <group>syscheck,fim_escalation,</group>
  </rule>

  <!-- Cluster membership config: a corosync.conf change means nodes added/removed. -->
  <rule id="100421" level="10">
    <if_sid>550,553,554</if_sid>
    <field name="file" type="pcre2">^/etc/pve/corosync\.conf$</field>
    <description>Proxmox FIM: /etc/pve/corosync.conf changed — possible unauthorised cluster membership change.</description>
    <mitre><id>T1489</id></mitre>
    <group>syscheck,fim_escalation,cluster_integrity,</group>
  </rule>

  <!-- Host/guest firewall config: rule bypass risk. Below gate (configured routinely). -->
  <rule id="100422" level="8">
    <if_sid>550,553,554</if_sid>
    <field name="file" type="pcre2">^/etc/pve/firewall/</field>
    <description>Proxmox FIM: PVE firewall configuration changed ($(file)) — verify authorised update.</description>
    <mitre><id>T1562.007</id></mitre>
    <group>syscheck,fim_escalation,</group>
  </rule>

  <!-- Storage / datacenter config — visibility (changed legitimately during admin work). -->
  <rule id="100423" level="7">
    <if_sid>550,553,554</if_sid>
    <field name="file" type="pcre2">^/etc/pve/(storage|datacenter)\.cfg$</field>
    <description>Proxmox FIM: PVE storage/datacenter configuration changed ($(file)).</description>
    <mitre><id>T1098</id></mitre>
    <group>syscheck,fim_escalation,</group>
  </rule>

</group>

<!-- ============================================================
     D. Proxmox-host auditd execve noise suppression
     These Wazuh-layer de-rates complement the source-level auditd never-rules
     (see audit-rules/99-wazuh-mitre.rules in this pack). The primary fix is the
     never-rule (audited at the kernel before Wazuh ever sees the event); this rule
     provides a second line of defence for transient or deployment windows where the
     never-rules are not yet applied.
     ============================================================ -->
<group name="proxmox,proxmox-ve,audit,audit_anom,">

  <!-- De-rate stock rule 80789 ("Audit: Watch - Execute access", L3) for the benign
       daemon-context mawk that Proxmox's own services run constantly (pvestatd polling
       /proc/meminfo, proxmox-firewall pipelines). Source: 24h execve histogram on a
       Proxmox host — ~1,763 events/24h, all auid=4294967295 (no login session), cwd=/.

       SCOPE / SAFETY: matches ONLY /usr/bin/mawk AND auid=4294967295 (daemon, no login
       session) AND cwd=/. A human running awk in a login session (auid set) still fires
       80789 at L3. A look-alike binary outside /usr/bin/mawk does NOT match. Offensive
       tooling is untouched — nmap/masscan still fire 200166 (T1046, L12), /tmp|/dev/shm
       exec still fires 200180 (L12).

       PROHIBITED from this suppression (must never be added here — would blind detection
       rules): nmap, nc, netcat, masscan, rustscan, hping3, socat, wget, curl, ssh.

       NOTE: the source-level fix (auditd never-rule for /usr/bin/mawk) is in
       audit-rules/99-wazuh-mitre.rules. This Wazuh rule is defense-in-depth only. -->
  <rule id="100023" level="1">
    <if_sid>80789</if_sid>
    <field name="audit.exe">^/usr/bin/mawk$</field>
    <field name="audit.auid">^4294967295$</field>
    <field name="audit.cwd">^/$</field>
    <description>Auditd: benign daemon mawk (Proxmox pvestatd/firewall polling, no login session) — de-rated</description>
    <group>audit,audit_anom,</group>
  </rule>

</group>
